{"parse":{"title":"Era Fascista","pageid":56545078,"revid":860597931,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:152px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Italia,_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III,_1928.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Italia%2C_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III%2C_1928.JPG/150px-Italia%2C_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III%2C_1928.JPG\" width=\"150\" height=\"146\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Italia%2C_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III%2C_1928.JPG/225px-Italia%2C_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III%2C_1928.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Italia%2C_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III%2C_1928.JPG/300px-Italia%2C_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III%2C_1928.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1087\" data-file-height=\"1059\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Italia,_20_lire_di_vittorio_emanuele_III,_1928.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A Fascist-period Italian coin dated MCMXXVIII&#160;A.VI</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>Era Fascista</b> was a calendar used in <a href=\"/wiki/Italian_Fascism\" title=\"Italian Fascism\">Fascist Italy</a>. The <a href=\"/wiki/March_on_Rome\" title=\"March on Rome\">March on Rome</a>, or more precisely the accession of <a href=\"/wiki/Mussolini\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mussolini\">Mussolini</a> as prime minister on 29 October 1922, is day 1 of <a href=\"/wiki/Epoch_(reference_date)\" title=\"Epoch (reference date)\">year I</a> of the Era Fascista. The calendar was introduced in 1926 and became official in Year 5 (1927).<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The Era Fascista calendar was inspired by the <a href=\"/wiki/French_Republican_Calendar\" title=\"French Republican Calendar\">French Republican Calendar</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Era Fascista dates consisted of the Gregorian date appended by the corresponding Era Fascista year in <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_numerals\" title=\"Roman numerals\">Roman numerals</a>, thus the date of Italy's declaration of war on Greece was written as \"28 October 1940 - XIX\". The Era Fascista year was sometimes written as \"Anno XIX\", \"A. XIX\", or marked \"E.F.\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>,  The calendar was intended to replace the \"bourgeois\" <a href=\"/wiki/Gregorian_calendar\" title=\"Gregorian calendar\">Gregorian calendar</a> in Italian public life to the extent that, in 1939, newspapers were forbidden to write about <a href=\"/wiki/New_Year%27s_Day\" title=\"New Year&#39;s Day\">New Year's Day</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:152px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Teatro_di_Marcello,_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Teatro_di_Marcello%2C_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg/150px-Teatro_di_Marcello%2C_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"200\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Teatro_di_Marcello%2C_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg/225px-Teatro_di_Marcello%2C_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Teatro_di_Marcello%2C_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg/300px-Teatro_di_Marcello%2C_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1536\" data-file-height=\"2048\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Teatro_di_Marcello,_anno_VII_EF_P1140343.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A plaque with fasces on the <a href=\"/wiki/Teatro_di_Marcello\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Teatro di Marcello\">Teatro di Marcello</a> dated A.&#160;VII&#160;E.F.</div></div></div>\n<p>The tenth anniversary of the March on Rome, Year X, was called the <i>Decennale</i> (evoking the ancient Roman <i><a href=\"/wiki/Decennalia\" title=\"Decennalia\">Decennalia</a></i>). The propaganda centerpiece of Year X was the <a href=\"/wiki/Exhibition_of_the_Fascist_Revolution\" title=\"Exhibition of the Fascist Revolution\">Exhibition of the Fascist Revolution</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The calendar was abandoned with the fall of Fascism in 1943 (Anno XXI), but many monuments in Italy still bear Era Fascista dates.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Era_Fascista&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Edgardo Baldi, Aldo Cerchiari, <i>Enciclopedia moderna italiana</i>, p. 1306</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Philip V. Cannistraro, \"Mussolini's cultural revolution: fascist or nationalist?\" in Roger Griffin, Matthew Feldman, eds., <i>Fascism: Fascism and Culture</i> in <i>Fascism: Critical Concept in Political Science</i> <b>3</b>:194, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/041529018X\" title=\"Special:BookSources/041529018X\">041529018X</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Catherine E. Paul, <i>Fascist Directive: Ezra Pound and Italian Cultural Nationalism</i>, 2016, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781942954057\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781942954057\">9781942954057</a>, p. 114</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Simonetta Falasca-Zamponi, <i>Fascist Spectacle: The Aesthetics of Power in Mussolini's Italy</i>, 2000, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0520226771\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0520226771\">0520226771</a>, p. 105</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">B. Painter, <i>Mussolini's Rome: Rebuilding the Eternal City</i>, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1403976910\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1403976910\">1403976910</a>, 2016, p. 26</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2178\nCached time: 20180921193221\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.092 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.123 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 968/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 4001/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 1509/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 15/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2270/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.011/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 830 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,tem